<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson5_6" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title> Quantum State Representation in Qiskit </title>

  <introduction>
    <p> Armed with our understanding of the mathematical representation, let's see how Qiskit
      represents quantum states, and how we can better understand how quantum operations are
      represented and executed in Qiskit.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="sec_qiskit_state_representation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>How Qiskit Represents Quantum States</title>
    <p> Qiskit stores a quantum state using a type of object called a <c>Statevector</c>. The easiest way to
      create a <c>Statevector</c> is using the <c>Statevector.from_label()</c> method. If you pass this function <c>"0"</c>, it will
      create the <m>\ket{0} = \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}</m> state, and if you pass it <c>"1"</c>, it will create the <m>\ket{1} = \begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m> state. </p>

    <cd>
      from qiskit.quantum_info import Statevector

      # Create the zero state
      state0 = Statevector.from_label("0")
    </cd>

    <p>Once we've created the <c>Statevector</c>, how can we display it? Qiskit lets you display a <c>Statevector</c> in <em>vector
      notation</em> using the <c>array_to_latex()</c> function.</p>

    <listing xml:id="statevector_from_label">
      <title>Initializing a <c>Statevector</c> using a label</title>
      <program xml:id="statevector_from_label_program" interactive="activecode" language="python3">
        <code>
          from qiskit.quantum_info import Statevector

          # Create the zero state
          state0 = Statevector.from_label("0")

          # Display the state
          array_to_latex(state0)
        </code>
      </program>
    </listing>

  </subsection>
</section>
